merica’s Philosopher shows how and why interpretations of his ideas have captivated Americans in ways few other philosophers—from any nation—ever have. As Arcenas makes clear, each generation has essentially remade Locke in its own image, taking inspiration and transmuting his ideas to suit the needs of the particular historical moment. Drawing from a host of vernacular sources to illuminate Locke’s often contradictory impact on American daily and intellectual life from before the Revolutionary War to the present, Arcenas delivers a pathbreaking work in the history of ideas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  ajohn locke, knowledge, epistemology, republicanism, identity, government, politics, father of liberalism, influence, legacy, philosophy, nonfiction, history, revolutionary war, authority, libertarian, toleration, tolerance, education, child-rearing, nation, founding, independence, agency, individual, enlightenment, empiricism, consciousness.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226820415423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226820415/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles